observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant make the necessary correcting journal entries in the General Fund and Trust Fund books for the cash transfer made in 2024 for the unexpended 2023 LDRRM Fund;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant revert back to the General Fund the unutilized LDRRM Fund of more than five years in the Trust Fund.
Henceforth, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant should record the transfer of unexpended balance of LDRRMF (QRF & MOOE) from the General Fund to Trust Fund at yearend, and also record the reversion of unutilized LDRRMF of more than five years in the Trust Fund to the General Fund.

We recommend that the Bids and Awards Committee follow strictly the rules and regulations set forth in the 2016 RIRR of RA 9184, specifically the following:

Fill out completely the clauses contained in the BDS and SCC, and incorporate the Specifications, Drawings and Bill of Quantities in the preparation of PBDs to provide prospective bidders all the necessary information that they need to prepare their bids;

Revise the invitation letters to observers to include their presence in all stages of the procurement;

Prepare the Checklist of Technical and Financial Component using the prescribed format indicated in the 6th Edition of PBDs.

Affix the BAC’s initials in the original copy of Technical Documents, including the Eligibility Documents and Financial Documents for purposes of authentication of submitted bids;

Prepare the Abstract of Bids as Read during opening of bids;

Indicate the date of preparation of the TWG Bid Evaluation Report and in all other documents;

Include in the notice to the bidder with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Bid the requirement to submit its latest income and business tax returns, and other appropriate licenses and permit required by law;

Require the BAC-TWG to state clearly in their Post Qualification Report that they have verified and validated all necessary eligibility requirements mentioned in Sections 23.1 and 25.2.b of the 2016 RIRR of R.A. 9184; and that they have confirmed the LRCB’s compliance with the requirements and conditions stated in the Bidding Documents;

Require the winning bidder to submit their DOLE-approved CSHP before approval of the contracts;

Post the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS website within three (3) and fifteen (15) calendar days from issuance, respectively; and

Follow the recommended minimum and maximum number of days to complete the entire procurement process from advertising/posting of IB up to the issuance of Notice of Award for the procurement of infrastructure projects as indicated in Annex C of the 2016 RIRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended the following:
a. The Inventory Committee shall conduct a physical inventory of the all the local road network under the LGU’s jurisdiction and reconcile the local road inventory with the records of the accounting office;
b. The Municipal GSO must maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for each road network;
c. The Municipal Engineer shall provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for all its local road networks with the help of the Municipal Assessor on the assessment of road lot component; and
d. The Municipal Accountant shall ensure that all local road networks and its component will be recorded in the book of accounts.

We recommended that the LCE -

	direct the Municipal Treasurer to perform functions pertaining to supply and property management and comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 7160 and MNGAS related thereto;

	review the personnel complement of the Municipality together with the current inventory management, and impose and implement control measures on the handling, safekeeping and disposal of inventories, such as proper segregation of duties and responsibilities, to prevent possible loss and misusage;

	avoid assigning incompatible functions, such as the issuance and custody of inventories, to only one person; and

	designate qualified personnel on functions requiring specific knowledge and competence, such as the dispensing of medicines, to provide correct medications and treatment.

