observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct the concerned officials to submit immediately all contracts and documents related to COVID-19 response;
b. Instruct the Municipal Engineer with the timely preparation and submission of POWs, and pakyaw contracts, and other supporting documents of PPAs implemented by administration;
c. Ensure enough manpower for the BAC Secretariat so that they can perform their duties effectively; and
d. Ensure the timely submission of copies of all government contracts and each of all the documents forming part thereof within five (5) working days from execution pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009, to ensure timely review and evaluation of the same, so that the Management could be immediately notified of any defects/deficiencies noted thereon.

We recommended that:
a. The BAC only accepts Purchase Request with items without specific brands;
b. The end user shall base the specifications of goods on relevant characteristics including but not limited to measures of performance, efficiency and other appropriate quality;
c. The BAC and TWG to always require the winning bidder of the Certification from the Insurance Company for every specific project for the Performance Security issued in the form of Surety bond; and
d. To strictly adhere with pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184.

We recommended that:
a. Require the MPDC to install Full Disclosure Bulletin Boards in at least three (3) accessible and conspicuous places in the Municipality;
b. Instruct the concerned department heads to update the posting of 14 reports enumerated in Section 3.2 of DILG MC No. 2019-149 as well as COVID-19 fund utilization reports as of December 31, 2020;
c. Henceforth observe the timeliness in the posting of the required operational reports at the designated places in order to attain maximum transparency in LGU governance.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Stop charging of ineligible expenses to GAD Fund;
b. Instruct the GAD Focal Person to submit the GAD AR and its supporting documents;
c. Maximize the utilization of the GAD fund for the year so that wider scope of intended beneficiaries can be benefited of the GAD programs, projects and activities, and objective of the fund can be fully achieved during the year;
d. Strictly adhere to the regulation in the utilization of the Gender and Development Fund in accordance with the provisions of Section 1.2 of Joint Circular No. 2012-01 of PCW, NEDA and DBM; and
e. Direct the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to facilitate the institution of GAD database to have a basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation and to undertake thorough gender analysis based on sex-disaggregated data for proper identification of PPAs that are responsive to address the gender issues.

We reiterated our recommendation that:
 Management see to it that a copy of the RPCPPE shall be submitted to COA for verification not later than January 31, of each year pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS; 
 General Services Officer maintain PPE Cards and ARE/PAR and ensure that the ARE/PAR be renewed every after three years pursuant to Section 492 of GAAM, Volume 1, to establish effective management and control over PPE; 
 General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant reconcile their property records with the result of physical count to ensure that PPE recorded in the property records really exists and that all existing PPE are recorded in the books, in order to establish correctness and completeness of balances of PPE accounts. Any variance shall be dealt accordingly and subsequently adjusted as necessary.
 The Property and Accounting Units comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.

We recommended that Management submit the following verifiable supporting documents to enable proper evaluation and appreciation of the COVID-19 response efforts of the Municipality:
 Lists of recipients, showing date of receipt, quantity and goods received, corresponding barangay and signature, for the distribution of relief goods worth ₱14,010,779.67;
 Lacking information per recipient of financial assistance, as tabulated under Item 15.6.6;
 For medicines and vitamins and medical supplies, verifiable procurement documents and distribution lists and or Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) supported with Requisition Issue Slip (RIS), as appropriate; and for Hospital Beds, the covering ARE; and
 Photograph documentations of the COVID-19 response aid and operations of the Municipality relative to the above expenditures, properly captioned and dated.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

MDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with COA No. Circular No. 2012-02;

BAC, BAC Secretariat and Accounting Office to i) submit the lacking documents; and ii) adhere to the GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 concerning emergency procurement of goods and the revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 on the conduct of public bidding;

MDRRMO to submit the required list of recipients with important details such as the actual quantity received, signature of the recipients, date received and the location of recipients for the COVID-19 related procurement for the proper evaluation thereof; and

Municipal Accountant to i) check and ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment; ii) prepare and submit the report on utilization of MDRRMF; and iii) disclose in the Notes to the FS information on the utilization of the MDRRMF.

We recommended that the management direct the MENRO to:

enjoin the nine (9) barangays noted and to immediately establish their respective MRFs pursuant to RA No. 9003 so that residual wastes will be minimized and relatively reduce the final disposal fee of garbage being paid by the municipality; and

 capacitate the households on how to segregate waste at source by conducting seminars and/or information drive for each barangay of the municipality;

We also recommended that the MSWMB headed by the Local Chief Executive as Chairman to:  

review and evaluate the implementation of the SWMP and impose prompt recording and accounting of the MRF from total production and corresponding sales;

institute other revenue-generating measures to promote and ensure the viability of its Solid Waste Management Plan.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:

Municipal Local School Board to (i) prepare programs and ensure approval of SEF budget within the indicative timeline as mandated in the DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017; and (ii) endeavor an optimal utilization of SEF budget in line with the State’s objectives of supplementing the needs of government schools;

Accounting Office to meticulously check the financial transactions and ensure that all required supporting documents are attached and necessary data/information are complete before payment;

Local Chief Executive to warrant sufficient staffing of the Accounting Office so as not to derail the processing of financial transactions and avoid accumulation of workloads of the current personnel; and

OIC-Accountant and all other personnel concerned to require certification from the DepEd Accountant that all expenses/disbursements to be charged to the SEF are net of the budgetary provision for the same or related item(s) in the budget for the DepEd and the ECCD Council.

